2\
\
Genius slept in vaults,\
night shining cloud,\
in blind lofts failing,\
of fires and falling ladders,\
but I could never see you.\
\
Sleeping wounded,\
written beneath his ribs,\
like the barbs of spires,\
a lonely priory,\
what he once named his soul.\
\
Hidden from the ebb and hiding,\
across that threshold,\
appearing and disappearing,\
this unyielding phenomenon,\
the Hazelnut fruited.\
\
Knots spread about my feet,\
sentenced in the arcade there,\
beneath that hide,\
the basilica\'92s soft tripe.\
\
Bloated as the seasons,\
the harvest shone from the labels of tin cans,\
the first rain tallow,\
the oceans aborted.\
\
The sea ruined across the coastline,\
the last light welt upon his tomb,\
at Blake\'92s door,\
where he threw down his fiery sword.\
\
His commandments and guard,\
no offices left, no chambers,\
no bed but pips upon the sill,\
sleepless vigils of chalk.\
\
My own bracing,\
mine own beat,\
soundly,\
wakeful.\
\
Distinct and imperceptible,\
before the gateway,\
watching,\
waiting.\
\
