\cf0 \
The river is restless in its pursuit of uncovering the land. Grass bristles in the coarse wind. Thick roots hold the earth together and the black sand on the bank washes away over petrified wood. A black pine box emerges in a shallow grave. The river pulls at his bones, begging him onwards with his cherished memories. His bills are in the eddy with the Elva, and his letters putrefy.\
\
Lights burn all night in the Masonic hall waiting on news from the James Webb. Fat moths arrive in the ancestral forest to feed on the resinous sap of familial trees. Inebriate and thirsty, they fall among the black pears on the ground, singing \'93Go Away Dream.\'94\
And on the estuary , a night watchman wades into the water from the brush. \'93Frog Man,\'94 he whispers to himself. With his arms above his head and his nose inches above the water, he stalks the stars as he disturbs the neat surface of night.\
\'93Poor Syrinx,\'94 he whispers. \'93Poor Syrinx.\'94\
\
In his mind the echoes of the day passed into memory- the sound of the radio as the sun dipped. The street lights orange. Today he held a picture of the cosmos in his hand. \
He felt as if he had seen the universe meet itself, The same planets and dust, reflected as if submerged in the water- coinciding in this strange artefact. The newspaper, the ink against his thumb. The weight of the print in his hands.\
\
Bodies, doppelg\'e4ngers, lay scattered across the page. \
We might be but a speck, yet the specks gleam back and back again forever. At the locus of each star system lies the edge of another- like a pebble caught between rocks, like sand between pebbles. The swill of sinew and roe against agates and opals, dashed upon the Lee.\
\
The pith, the Nutmeg, the Coriander. Across the ocean from breaking waves. Flat, breaking, acrid, and malt, emptying on the shore. The foam forms and unforms in the glass. An indifferent pattern. A subtle thing, shrunken away. Like the pebble, like the marble to the satellite. A small flat world floating like the film on this beer. Broken on the rocks. An ammonium wash on the water.\
\
Sipping from his Budweiser, he makes the sign, crossing himself; imagining the crucifix, kissing it, and releasing it back to the water like a tadpole.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
He pushes forward, occasionally submerging his head into the Bullrush and weeds that hang just beneath the brackish water, gliding. Almost imperceptible in the dark, the black spots of his head vanish from view. With one arm still firmly reaching out of the water, two red embers float toward the Weir. Water crests, glittering over the edge of the walls. \
\
The surface is glassy and pleated over the pond. One hand finds the far bank with no warning, lost in dark muck. He finds the opaque water suddenly terrifying again as his fingers find holds in the dirt.\uc0\u8232  The Weir pulls at him, and the temptations of St. Anthony writhe around his fingers. \
He traces the slick holes that dot the banking before thrusting into a wide one. \'93In shallows and miseries,\'94 the words wet. The hole shudders, he shudders. \'93Christ,\'94 he says.\uc0\u8232 The muscle try to shoot past his arm, but he grips it firmly.\
\
Suddenly, the silence is full of water, a dull thud and little bells. \'93Go away, stalker of terrible dread!\'94 he exclaims.\uc0\u8232 \'93This monstrous, wayward mother. Behemoth!\'94\u8232  Onlookers who had watched in silent disbelief begin to jeer.\u8232  \'93Go, go, hell spawn, go incubus,\'94 he cries as he drags the strange beast through the widow grass. A Mallard barks from the trees. The Crickets\'92 song seems to start right there.\u8232 \'93Go away, brass, you dog.\'94\
\
He stands up from the water, the sky pouring from his shoulders. He quickly drags on his cigarette in celebration, lifting the dark Eel above his head. \'93Old George,\'94 they cheer, their voices alien over the water. \'93You crazy bastard.\'94\
\uc0\u8232 The red ember lights his sodden features as he smokes. He takes the Eel in both hands and begins to sing.\u8232 \'93Old George, no scratch. Wet to the bone. Fluted and pipes, Clean as the wind blows.\'94\u8232  He looks down at his catch, no longer fighting him, the yellow sheen. Her skin glows, her belly like flashes of moonlight. Her ribs like the glassy water. \u8232 \'93Of the sun and of the air!\'94\
\uc0\u8232 \'93Toil, toil,\'94 the Eel replies.\
\
The cigarette quickly sizzles into quietness on the water.\
\
He holds her against his chest and drops back into the pool, kicking his legs out gently as he pushes back towards the celebration that erupted beyond the thick reeds on the other side of the river.\
\uc0\u8232 The other men grow silent again when they lose him from sight, with no ember this time to help trace his path. The image of that Eel dripping in the moonlight stays with them, entranced, like a white flash or a trick of the eye. Every speck of blackness tussles in the darkness. The sky is so dim now they see blue fire where they had been able to make out shapes and forms in the moonlight.\
\
The Crickets fall silent. The Mallard chuckles.\
\
He does not flinch. He wades out to the middle of the pond on his back, cautious of the Eel suddenly trying to escape. But the Eel remains placid.\
\
He looks from the sky back into her eyes and begins to beg for answers. The Eels mouth slowly opens and closes. \
\'91I wish\'85,\'92 He began.\
\'93Damn this water, this bastard Weir! Heed my warning, child!\'94 The Eel interrupted. \'93Thy tabret has been beaten. Cast out. Your bookkeeping lost across the fertile beach of the tidal river. Treading bridge ash on the banks of your enemies. Collapsed into your base.\'94\
The man stiffens, the water rising around him as though it too is listening, waiting.\
\'93To hell! Your story isn\'92t written. My fates are my own,\'94 the man exclaims.\
Her unflinching eyes gleam back at him.\
\'93Houses upon houses, ashes and ashes, double, double, and dust to dust,\'94 spoke the Eel. \'93Be wary of greener pastures.\'94\
The man shudders again. \
\'93A grim omen. Tsk\'85 if the grass looks greener, how will I judge, if avoiding my ill fate is greener still? Do you not know another way?\'94\
\
\'93Follow me,\'94 she whispers.\
